name: 3e Gymnopédie
comments: 3eme Gymnopédie is part of The Gymnopédies or Trois Gymnopédies, three piano compositions. Satie completed the whole set as a manuscript by April 2, 1888, but after this the 3 parts were published individually: the third in November 1888, the first and the second in 1895. 3eme Gymnopédie was dedicated to composer Conrad Levadé on the first publication in 1888. The three short, atmospheric pieces are written in 3/4 time, with each sharing a common theme and structure. 1re Gymnopédie Lent et douloureux (D major / D minor) 2e Gymnopédie Lent et triste (C major) 3e Gymnopédie Lent et grave (A minor) By the end of 1896, Satie's popularity was waning and financial situation deteriorating. Claude Debussy a friend of Satie's whose popularity was on the rise, helped draw public attention to Satie's work. In February 1897, Debussy orchestrated the third and first Gymnopédies. When Debussy published the scores two years later, he reversed the numbering, with Satie's first becoming Debussy's third, and vice versa.

name: 2e Gymnopédie
comments: 2e Gymnopédie is part of Gymnopédies or Trois Gymnopédies, three piano compositions. Satie completed the whole set as a manuscript by April 2, 1888, but after this the 3 parts were published individually: the third in November 1888, the first and the second in 1895. 2e Gymnopédie was dedicated to his brother Conrad Satie on the first publication in 1895 (but on the manuscript from April 1888 it was dedicated to his friend (mon ami) Arthur Dodement though) The three short, atmospheric pieces are written in 3/4 time, with each sharing a common theme and structure. 1re Gymnopédie Lent et douloureux (D major / D minor) 2e Gymnopédie Lent et triste (C major) 3e Gymnopédie Lent et grave (A minor) By the end of 1896, Satie's popularity was waning and financial situation deteriorating. Claude Debussy a friend of Satie's whose popularity was on the rise, helped draw public attention to Satie's work. In February 1897, Debussy orchestrated the third and first Gymnopédies. When Debussy published the scores two years later, he reversed the numbering, with Satie's first becoming Debussy's third, and vice versa.

comments: A plowboy and a rich girl fall in love. When the girl's father finds out, he sends a press gang for the boy. And they sent him to the wars to be slain. The girl dresses in men's clothes and rows out to her lover's ship. She bribes the captain to return her lover. [Roud 186 ; Master title: The Pretty Ploughboy ; Laws M24 ; G/D 1:170 ; Henry H105 ; Ballad Index LM24 ; Bodleian Roud 186 ; GlosTrad Roud 186 ; Wiltshire 50 , 198 , 938 ; trad.] First sheet music published in Nottingham, England between 1797-1807. Lyrics of first verse; It’s of a brisk young ploughboy, he was ploughing on the plain, And his horses stood down in yonder shade. It was down in yonder grove, he went whistling to his plough, And by chance there he met a pretty maid, pretty maid, And by chance there he met a pretty maid.
